  <section id="why-critical" style="margin-bottom:2rem;">
    <h2 style="font-size:1.15rem; font-weight:700; color:#1e293b; margin-bottom:0.75rem; padding-bottom:0.5rem; border-bottom:2px solid #e2e8f0;">Why Is Critical Thinking Important in Nursing?</h2>
    <p style="line-height:1.8; color:#374151; margin-bottom:1rem;"><strong>Definition:</strong> Critical thinking in nursing is the purposeful, outcome-directed, reflective, and disciplined cognitive process of analyzing clinical information to make sound clinical judgments and provide safe, effective patient care.</p>
    <p style="line-height:1.8; color:#374151; margin-bottom:1rem;"><strong>Why it is essential:</strong></p>
    <ul style="line-height:1.8; color:#374151; margin-bottom:1rem; padding-left:1.5rem;">
      <li><strong>Patient safety:</strong> Nursing errors — medication errors, failure to rescue, falls — frequently result from failures in clinical reasoning, not lack of knowledge. A nurse who thinks critically catches errors before they reach the patient.</li>
      <li><strong>Complex, rapidly changing patients:</strong> No two patients are alike; textbook knowledge must be adapted in real time. Critical thinking bridges knowledge and action.</li>
      <li><strong>Information overload:</strong> Nurses receive vast amounts of data every shift (assessments, labs, orders, monitoring). Critical thinking filters what is significant.</li>
      <li><strong>Advocacy:</strong> Critical thinkers recognize when something is wrong, even if they can't immediately name it, and advocate for patients accordingly.</li>
      <li><strong>Ethical decision-making:</strong> Nurses regularly face ethical dilemmas; critical thinking helps weigh competing values and apply ethical frameworks systematically.</li>
      <li><strong>NCLEX and clinical competency:</strong> The Next Generation NCLEX (NGN) tests clinical judgment, not just recall — specifically measuring how nurses recognize cues, analyze data, prioritize hypotheses, generate solutions, take action, and evaluate outcomes.</li>
    </ul>
    <div style="background:#eff6ff; border-left:3px solid #3b82f6; padding:1rem; margin-bottom:1rem; border-radius:0 0.5rem 0.5rem 0;">
      <strong>Attributes of a critical thinker in nursing:</strong> Curious, open-minded, analytical, systematic, confident, creative, flexible, fair-minded, willing to reconsider, self-aware.
    </div>
  </section>

  <section id="q1" style="margin-bottom:2rem;">
    <h2 style="font-size:1.15rem; font-weight:700; color:#1e293b; margin-bottom:0.75rem; padding-bottom:0.5rem; border-bottom:2px solid #e2e8f0;">Q1: What Are the Steps in Correctly Teaching a Patient to Use Crutches?</h2>
    <div style="background:#f0fdf4; border:1px solid #bbf7d0; border-radius:0.5rem; padding:1rem; margin-bottom:1rem;">
      <p style="font-weight:700; color:#166534; margin-bottom:0.5rem;">Answer:</p>
      <ol style="line-height:1.8; color:#166534; padding-left:1.5rem; margin:0;">
        <li>Assess the patient's upper body strength, balance, weight-bearing status, and motivation to learn</li>
        <li>Explain the purpose of crutches and the type of gait they will use (non-weight-bearing, partial weight-bearing)</li>
        <li>Measure crutches correctly: tip 6 inches lateral and 2 inches anterior to foot; top 2–3 finger-widths below axilla; elbow flexed 20–30° at handgrip</li>
        <li>Demonstrate the prescribed gait pattern on flat surface (3-point gait for non-weight-bearing: advance both crutches and injured leg together, then swing good leg forward)</li>
        <li>Have the patient return demonstrate on flat surface while you observe and correct technique</li>
        <li>Teach and practice stair climbing: "Up with the good, down with the bad" (ascend with strong leg first; descend with crutches and injured leg first)</li>
        <li>Teach safety measures: no weight on axilla (nerve damage risk), check rubber tips daily, use non-slip footwear, keep floors clear, report numbness/tingling</li>
        <li>Provide written instructions for home reference</li>
        <li>Evaluate understanding using teach-back; document teaching and patient response before discharge</li>
      </ol>
    </div>
  </section>

  <section id="q2" style="margin-bottom:2rem;">
    <h2 style="font-size:1.15rem; font-weight:700; color:#1e293b; margin-bottom:0.75rem; padding-bottom:0.5rem; border-bottom:2px solid #e2e8f0;">Q2: What Are the Steps to Insert a Foley Catheter?</h2>
    <div style="background:#f0fdf4; border:1px solid #bbf7d0; border-radius:0.5rem; padding:1rem; margin-bottom:1rem;">
      <p style="font-weight:700; color:#166534; margin-bottom:0.5rem;">Answer (Indwelling urinary catheter — sterile technique):</p>
      <ol style="line-height:1.8; color:#166534; padding-left:1.5rem; margin:0;">
        <li>Verify order; explain procedure; provide privacy; position patient (female: dorsal recumbent; male: supine)</li>
        <li>Perform hand hygiene; open sterile catheter kit using sterile technique; don sterile gloves</li>
        <li>Organize sterile field: drape, antiseptic swabs, lubricant, catheter, syringe with sterile water for balloon</li>
        <li>Place sterile fenestrated drape over perineum</li>
        <li><strong>Female:</strong> With non-dominant hand, separate labia and maintain position (now contaminated); clean meatus front to back with 3 swabs. <strong>Male:</strong> Grasp penis at 90°, retract foreskin, clean meatus in circular outward motion with 3 swabs.</li>
        <li>Lubricate catheter tip; insert gently until urine flows (female: 2–3 inches; male: 7–9 inches)</li>
        <li>Advance 1 more inch after urine flows; inflate balloon with ordered sterile water (typically 10 mL)</li>
        <li>Gently pull catheter back until resistance felt (balloon against bladder neck)</li>
        <li>Connect to closed drainage system; secure catheter to inner thigh (female) or upper thigh/lower abdomen (male); hang drainage bag below bladder</li>
        <li>Replace foreskin (male); remove drapes; document: time, catheter size, amount of urine drained, color/clarity</li>
      </ol>
    </div>
  </section>

  <section id="q3" style="margin-bottom:2rem;">
    <h2 style="font-size:1.15rem; font-weight:700; color:#1e293b; margin-bottom:0.75rem; padding-bottom:0.5rem; border-bottom:2px solid #e2e8f0;">Q3: What Are the Stages of Wounds?</h2>
    <div style="background:#f0fdf4; border:1px solid #bbf7d0; border-radius:0.5rem; padding:1rem; margin-bottom:1rem;">
      <p style="font-weight:700; color:#166534; margin-bottom:0.5rem;">Answer:</p>
      <p style="color:#166534; margin-bottom:0.5rem;"><strong>Pressure Injury Staging (NPIAP):</strong></p>
      <ul style="line-height:1.8; color:#166534; padding-left:1.5rem; margin-bottom:0.75rem;">
        <li><strong>Stage I:</strong> Non-blanchable erythema of intact skin. Skin intact but reddened area does not turn white with pressure. Localized, usually over bony prominence.</li>
        <li><strong>Stage II:</strong> Partial thickness skin loss — open shallow wound with red-pink wound bed; intact or ruptured blister. No slough.</li>
        <li><strong>Stage III:</strong> Full thickness skin loss. Subcutaneous fat visible. Slough may be present. No bone, tendon, or muscle exposed. May have undermining/tunneling.</li>
        <li><strong>Stage IV:</strong> Full thickness tissue loss with exposed bone, tendon, or muscle. Slough or eschar present. Often includes undermining and tunneling.</li>
        <li><strong>Unstageable:</strong> Full thickness loss with wound base obscured by slough or eschar — true depth cannot be determined until removed.</li>
        <li><strong>Deep Tissue Pressure Injury (DTPI):</strong> Persistent non-blanchable deep red, maroon, or purple discoloration; intact or non-intact skin. Represents damage to soft tissue from intense/prolonged pressure.</li>
      </ul>
      <p style="color:#166534; margin-bottom:0.5rem;"><strong>Phases of wound healing:</strong></p>
      <ul style="line-height:1.8; color:#166534; padding-left:1.5rem; margin:0;">
        <li><strong>Hemostasis:</strong> Immediate — vasoconstriction, platelet plug, clot formation</li>
        <li><strong>Inflammation (days 1–4):</strong> Vasodilation, WBC migration, phagocytosis of debris and bacteria; redness, warmth, swelling, pain are NORMAL</li>
        <li><strong>Proliferation (days 4–21):</strong> Granulation tissue formation, angiogenesis, wound contraction, re-epithelialization</li>
        <li><strong>Maturation/Remodeling (21 days – 2 years):</strong> Collagen remodeling; scar strengthens to ~80% of original tissue strength</li>
      </ul>
    </div>
  </section>

  <section id="q4" style="margin-bottom:2rem;">
    <h2 style="font-size:1.15rem; font-weight:700; color:#1e293b; margin-bottom:0.75rem; padding-bottom:0.5rem; border-bottom:2px solid #e2e8f0;">Q4: How Do You Communicate with a Family Member Who Has Just Lost a Loved One?</h2>
    <div style="background:#f0fdf4; border:1px solid #bbf7d0; border-radius:0.5rem; padding:1rem; margin-bottom:1rem;">
      <p style="font-weight:700; color:#166534; margin-bottom:0.5rem;">Answer:</p>
      <ul style="line-height:1.8; color:#166534; padding-left:1.5rem; margin:0;">
        <li><strong>Be present:</strong> Go to the family immediately; sit down with them in a private space</li>
        <li><strong>Use the person's name:</strong> "I'm so sorry about the loss of [name]." — personalizes and honors the deceased</li>
        <li><strong>Be honest and clear:</strong> Explain what happened in simple, compassionate language; avoid medical jargon</li>
        <li><strong>Allow silence:</strong> Do not rush to fill every pause; silence communicates your willingness to stay</li>
        <li><strong>Validate emotions:</strong> "It's okay to cry. This is an enormous loss."</li>
        <li><strong>Listen more than you speak:</strong> Let family members share memories and feelings without redirecting</li>
        <li><strong>Offer to have them see the loved one:</strong> Prepare the patient's appearance; allow as much time as needed</li>
        <li><strong>Connect with support resources:</strong> Offer chaplain, social worker, bereavement counselor</li>
        <li><strong>Avoid:</strong> "I know how you feel," "They're in a better place," "Stay strong," "Everything happens for a reason"</li>
      </ul>
    </div>
  </section>

  <section id="q5" style="margin-bottom:2rem;">
    <h2 style="font-size:1.15rem; font-weight:700; color:#1e293b; margin-bottom:0.75rem; padding-bottom:0.5rem; border-bottom:2px solid #e2e8f0;">Q5: What Is Assault? Battery? Libel? With Examples.</h2>
    <div style="background:#f0fdf4; border:1px solid #bbf7d0; border-radius:0.5rem; padding:1rem; margin-bottom:1rem;">
      <p style="font-weight:700; color:#166534; margin-bottom:0.5rem;">Answer:</p>
      <ul style="line-height:1.8; color:#166534; padding-left:1.5rem; margin:0;">
        <li><strong>Assault:</strong> A threat or act that causes a patient to fear harmful or offensive contact — no physical touch required. <em>Example: A nurse says, "If you don't stop yelling, I'll sedate you." This causes the patient to fear unwanted medication — assault.</em></li>
        <li><strong>Battery:</strong> Intentional, harmful, or offensive touching without the patient's consent. <em>Example: A nurse administers a medication after the patient clearly refuses it. Even with good intentions, this is battery.</em></li>
        <li><strong>Libel:</strong> Written defamation — publishing a false statement of fact that damages a person's reputation. <em>Example: A nurse writes in the medical record, "Patient is lying about her pain to get opioids" — if this is unfounded opinion stated as fact, it constitutes libel.</em> (Slander is the verbal equivalent.)</li>
      </ul>
    </div>
  </section>

  <section id="q6" style="margin-bottom:2rem;">
    <h2 style="font-size:1.15rem; font-weight:700; color:#1e293b; margin-bottom:0.75rem; padding-bottom:0.5rem; border-bottom:2px solid #e2e8f0;">Q6: What Are the Steps of the Nursing Process?</h2>
    <div style="background:#f0fdf4; border:1px solid #bbf7d0; border-radius:0.5rem; padding:1rem; margin-bottom:1rem;">
      <p style="font-weight:700; color:#166534; margin-bottom:0.5rem;">Answer (ADPIE):</p>
      <ol style="line-height:1.8; color:#166534; padding-left:1.5rem; margin:0;">
        <li><strong>Assessment:</strong> Collect subjective (patient-reported) and objective (measurable) data through interview, physical examination, review of records, and diagnostic results. Assessment is continuous.</li>
        <li><strong>Diagnosis:</strong> Analyze data to identify nursing diagnoses — clinical judgments about actual or potential health problems that nurses are licensed to treat (NANDA-I format: Problem related to Etiology as evidenced by Signs/Symptoms — PES format).</li>
        <li><strong>Planning:</strong> Set measurable patient-centered outcomes (SMART goals); select evidence-based nursing interventions; prioritize using Maslow's hierarchy; document the care plan; include patient in planning.</li>
        <li><strong>Implementation:</strong> Carry out nursing interventions — independent (within RN scope, no order needed), dependent (require a provider order — medications, procedures), and collaborative (with other healthcare team members). Use safe technique; document all actions.</li>
        <li><strong>Evaluation:</strong> Compare patient outcomes to the expected goals. Was the goal met, partially met, or not met? Revise the care plan as needed. The nursing process cycles continuously — evaluation leads back to reassessment.</li>
      </ol>
    </div>
  </section>

  <section id="q7" style="margin-bottom:2rem;">
    <h2 style="font-size:1.15rem; font-weight:700; color:#1e293b; margin-bottom:0.75rem; padding-bottom:0.5rem; border-bottom:2px solid #e2e8f0;">Q7: What Is the First Step in Taking Care of a Patient from a Different Culture?</h2>
    <div style="background:#f0fdf4; border:1px solid #bbf7d0; border-radius:0.5rem; padding:1rem; margin-bottom:1rem;">
      <p style="font-weight:700; color:#166534; margin-bottom:0.5rem;">Answer:</p>
      <p style="line-height:1.8; color:#166534; margin-bottom:0.5rem;">The first step is <strong>assessment</strong> — specifically, conducting a <strong>cultural assessment</strong> of the patient's individual beliefs, values, practices, and preferences. Do not assume anything based on appearance, ethnicity, or perceived background. Ask respectfully:</p>
      <ul style="line-height:1.8; color:#166534; padding-left:1.5rem; margin:0;">
        <li>"Are there any cultural, religious, or spiritual practices that are important to you and that we should know about as we care for you?"</li>
        <li>Assess language needs — arrange for a trained medical interpreter if English is not the primary language (never rely on family members or minors for medical interpretation)</li>
        <li>Identify dietary restrictions, modesty requirements, and preferences for same-gender caregivers</li>
        <li>Explore traditional healing practices the patient may be using</li>
        <li>Ask about family decision-making structure (individual vs. family-centered decision-making)</li>
      </ul>
    </div>
  </section>

  <section id="q8" style="margin-bottom:2rem;">
    <h2 style="font-size:1.15rem; font-weight:700; color:#1e293b; margin-bottom:0.75rem; padding-bottom:0.5rem; border-bottom:2px solid #e2e8f0;">Q8: What Is the Most Important Thing During the Assessment Part of the Nursing Process?</h2>
    <div style="background:#f0fdf4; border:1px solid #bbf7d0; border-radius:0.5rem; padding:1rem; margin-bottom:1rem;">
      <p style="font-weight:700; color:#166534; margin-bottom:0.5rem;">Answer:</p>
      <p style="line-height:1.8; color:#166534; margin-bottom:0.5rem;">The most important thing during assessment is <strong>collecting complete, accurate, and objective data</strong> — both subjective (the patient's own words about their experience) and objective (measurable clinical findings). Every subsequent step of the nursing process depends on the quality of assessment data; a poor assessment leads to incorrect diagnoses, inappropriate plans, and unsafe care.</p>
      <p style="line-height:1.8; color:#166534; margin-bottom:0.5rem;"><strong>Key principles:</strong></p>
      <ul style="line-height:1.8; color:#166534; padding-left:1.5rem; margin:0;">
        <li><strong>Build a therapeutic relationship:</strong> Patients who feel safe and respected share more complete information. Introduce yourself, maintain eye contact, sit at eye level, and ensure privacy.</li>
        <li><strong>Use open-ended questions first:</strong> "Tell me what brought you in today." Open questions yield richer information than yes/no questions.</li>
        <li><strong>Listen actively — not just for words but for emotions, hesitation, and what is NOT said.</strong></li>
        <li><strong>Be non-judgmental:</strong> Patients must feel safe to disclose sensitive information (substance use, abuse, sexual health, non-adherence). Judgment closes the conversation.</li>
        <li><strong>Collect both subjective AND objective data:</strong> Never rely solely on self-report or solely on objective findings; both perspectives are required.</li>
        <li><strong>Validate and clarify:</strong> Confirm your understanding. "So if I'm understanding correctly, the pain started yesterday after you lifted something heavy — is that right?"</li>
      </ul>
    </div>
  </section>

